        "## 3. Phase I – The Chronological Roster\n",
        "\n",
        "### Problem Description\n",
        "In this phase, we manage a crew member’s flight roster. The main requirement is that all flights must always stay in chronological order based on departure time. We also need to cancel a flight by ID, validate 12 hour rest between consecutive flights and display roster.\n",
        "\n",
        "### **We Choose Singly Linked List as our Data Structure**\n",
        "\n",
        "This is because in a singly linked list:\n",
        "- we can insert flights in sorted order without shifting elements and  supports sequential traversal, which is exactly what we need to insert a flight in the correct position.\n",
        "- memory is efficient compared to doubly linked list because no backward traversal is required, so the extra `prev` pointer of a doubly linked list would waste memory.\n",
        "- Deletion of a flight can be performed by traversing with a trailing pointer.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why we do NOT choose other structures**  \n",
        "\n",
        "**Doubly linked list** - this is a best alternative after singly linked list. It is not the best because\n",
        "- It allows backward traversal but we do not need it. It also uses extra memory for previous pointers making it less efficient than Singly linked list.Using DLL here is just over engineering.  \n",
        "\n",
        "**Stack**\n",
        "- Stack uses LIFO (Last in First Out) method so it does not allow chronolical scheduling  \n",
        "\n",
        "**Queue**  \n",
        "- Queue use FIFO(First In First Out) method. This is better than stack but it orders flights based on arrival order not by time order. This assignment explicitly tell us to handle out-of-order insertions, so neither a stack nor a queue can serve as the primary structure here.\n"
