        "### Critique and Reflection for Phase I\n",
        "\n",
        "The singly linked list is a natural fit for a chronological roster. We say this because it allows forward traversal and ordered insertion with minimal overhead. However, its main limitation is the inability to move backward like if we ever needed to traverse the roster in reverse (For example, to check rest from the end), we would be forced to restart from the head each time. In our case, forward traversal is sufficient for the qustion, so the simplicity and memory efficiency justifies our choice.\n",
        "\n",
        "If we had chosen a doubly linked list, deletion would become slightly easier (no need for a trailing pointer). But it comes at the cost of an extra pointer per node and more complex insertion. Given the typical roster size (a few dozen flights per month), the memory saving of a singly linked list is negligible, but the conceptual simplicity is valuable. Under heavy load with many cancellations, the O(n) deletion might become a bottleneck, but for this simulation it is acceptable.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The performance degrades if a crew member uses a very large number of flights,  the O(n) insertion cost could become a bottleneck. In a production system, a self-balancing binary search tree or skip list might be considered for O(log n) sorted insertion. However, for the scale modeled in this assignment, O(n) is entirely acceptable."
