        "## 5. Phase III – Equipment-Rated Standby Pool\n",
        "\n",
        "##Problem Description\n",
        "\n",
        "In this phase, we are required to manage a standby pool of crew members that can replace unavailable crew memebers when needed. Each of these standby crew member is associated with a specific aircraft rating (e.g., A380, B777). With this information provided, the key requirement is that when a crew member replacement is needed, the chosen crew member must match the  aircraft rating of the required aircraft type. Additionally, we are required to search for this crew member with matching aircraft type sequentially from the pool of standby crew members.\n",
        "\n",
        "## We chose Queue as our Data Structure\n",
        "###**Reason**\n",
        "We chose Queue because it aligns best with what we are required to perform. Queue data structure retrives stored information sequentially, which is exactly what is required of us to do in this phase.\n",
        "Additionally, Queue's retrival of stored information follows FIFO (First In First Out) which is what is needed in this phase to keep the integrity and order of the original stored information.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Why we do not use other data structures\n",
        "\n",
        "###***Stack***\n",
        "\n",
        "A stack follows LIFO (Last In First Out), which reverses the order of the crew members being assigned to a specific aircraft. Therefore, as this structure breaks the requirement to preserve the original order of the standby pool of replacement crew members.\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore, we haven't used this data strucutre as our main data structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "###***Linked Lists***\n",
        "\n",
        "When using Linked List, we can ofcourse traverse through the crews stored in the order required. Nevertheless, the reason why we didn't choose this structure is because in this phase we are required to remove temporarily a crewmember not matching the required aircraft type. Now, maintaining this is better achieved when using Queue as it becomes complex if tried to achieve this on Linked List.\n",
        "\n",
        "##**How we achieved temporarily removing a crew member without matching aircraft type while maintaining the original order of the stored data**\n",
        "\n",
        "For this specific task we have used two Queues, where the function will traverse through the entire Queue storing the crewmember information and removing the first crewmember found with matching aircraft information, it will enqueue the rest of the cremembers, into a new queue which will be used as the data structure holding all the rest of standby pool of crewmembers with their order intact.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is demonstrated in a general algorithm demonstration below.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
