        "## 5. Phase IV – Priority Briefing Dispatch\n",
        "\n",
        "##Problem Description\n",
        "\n",
        "In this phase, when crew members arrive at the briefing center before departure, we are required to ensure two things:\n",
        "1. We must ensure that they must be dispatched to their aircraft based on the order they arrive.\n",
        "2. If a crewmember with an earliest departure time exist, even if not the first to arrive at the briefing center, this crewmember must be given priority and dispatched first.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## We chose Queue as our Data Structure\n",
        "###**Reason**\n",
        "We chose to use Queue as our main data structure because it has a FIFO retrival of the nodes which fits perfectly with our first requirement of dispatching crewmembers in the order they arrive at the briefing center.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Why we do not use other data structures\n",
        "\n",
        "###***Singly Linked List***\n",
        "\n",
        "A singly linked list seems to fit well to our need in this phase, however, it doesn't enforce FIFO behaviour naturally, and inorder to manage insertion and removal of nodes, it requires more complexity compared to Queue. Therefore, although it was a good contendor, we chose to stick with Queue\n",
        "\n",
        "###***Doubly Linked List***\n",
        "\n",
        "This data structure is similar in its benefits to a linked list, but what makes it different is supporting a traversal option of going in both directions with the cost of extra memory overhead inorder to store a previous pointer. However, this phase's dispatch logic does not require backward traversal, thus this structure is inefficient for our requirement.\n",
        "\n",
        "###***Stack***\n",
        "\n",
