        "\n",
        "## 9.1 Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "In this assignment, we designed and implemented the Emirates Integrated Crew Resource Management (ICRM) System, a four-phase simulation of airline crew operations. Each phase used a carefully chosen custom data structure:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Phase I** used a **Singly Linked List** to maintain a chronologically sorted monthly flight roster. We implemented sorted insertion, deletion by ID, rest gap validation, and ordered display.\n",
        "- **Phase II** used a **Doubly Linked List** to represent the global fleet database. We implemented a bidirectional search that simultaneously traverses the list from both the head and the tail using two pointers that advance toward each other.\n",
        "- **Phase III** used a **Queue** to model the standby crew pool. We implemented sequential search with temporary removal and full order-preserving restoration of non-matching crew members.\n",
        "- **Phase IV** used a **Queue** to model the pre-flight briefing center. We implemented FIFO arrival-order dispatch with captain notification.\n",
        "\n",
        "We followed all implementation constraints: no Python built-in lists or dictionaries were used as core structures, all operations were implemented manually through node manipulation, and every method was accompanied by a written algorithm and pseudocode.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.2 Final Reflection\n",
        "\n",
        "This assignment thought us that the right data structure is determined by the access pattern of the problem, not by how complex or powerful the structure is.\n",
        "\n",
        "We did not choose a doubly linked list for every phase simply because it is more flexible than a singly linked list. We chose each structure because its properties aligned precisely with the operations we needed:\n",
